The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Bangalore firm in buy mode
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Bangalore firm in buy mode
          A STAFF REPORTER                              
	Calcutta, April 19: Bangalore-based Aditi Technologies  a software product and application development services company  has signed an agreement with Nasdaq-listed Infospace Inc to acquire the latters Indian subsidiary, Infospace India Software Development Pvt Ltd, for an undisclosed amount.         
	Infospace India is a metasearch and online consumer product company with a development centre in Bangalore.        
	The acquisition of Infospace aligns well with our focus of establishing an account base of stable and long-term engagements and further highlights the trust that leading software vendors have in our ability to deliver quality products faster, said Pradeep Rathinam, CEO of Aditi Technologies.         
	The terms of the transaction have been approved by the board of directors of both the firms.         
	This arrangement provides us with the operational efficiency and continued access to quality engineering talent needed to drive our product development strategy, said Leo Chang, chief technology officer of Infospace.         
	We look forward to strengthening our relationship with Aditi and their continued support, he said.                                                  
	Prodapt buy        
	Jhaver Groups software services firm Prodapt today acquired US-based Pacific Crest Technology in an all-cash deal for an undisclosed amount.         
	Pacific Crest is a $17.2-million (approximately Rs 80 crore) company with its headquarters in Oregon, US.         
	The buyout will expand Prodapts base in North America and consolidate its US operations, the company said.        
	Pacific Crest will be renamed Prodapt North America, with Pacific Crest CEO Kerry Padrick as its president.         
	Prodapt has worked with Pacific Crest Technology for over four years, delivering software services to large telecom operators. Over these years, we have built a strategic partnership between the companies for the US. This consolidation will strengthen our delivery capabilities for both wireline and wireless operators, Prodapt CEO Vedant Jhaver said.                                                                                                                                      
